snippet.textDisplay: As a 50+ year old investor, I dumped my 10k shares of Carlyle Group stock over this deal. Primarily because all the negative press will drive down the stock price. Secondly, what Borchetta did was dirty on both ends: 1) He wouldn't sell her her master's or even offer them to her. And, 2) he set Braun up for failure because the master's won't be worth 30% of their value when Taylor re-records them.  I also believe that you, the 100 million + Taylor Swift fans, will support her when she releases her new recordings and that will further drive down the value of the original master's. Scooter and his investment group screwed up on this deal. Also,after hearing this speach, how many artists will even think about signing with Braun? I doubt many, it any.  He's hurt his brand and the trust of his artists along with his investors.  Bad business deal all around. Had they sold her the master's, they would have profited.  Now, everyone loses but Taylor and her fans. I doubt anyone in Hollywood will touch the use of her master's from Braun because the backlash won't be worth the benefit of using her old music.  I've encouraged my investor friends to dump their Carlyle stock of plan to sell short because this will have a much larger impact than they thought.  Especially if Swift fans tell their investment friends and families to bail on Carlyle.  I might be wrong, because they are a $200 billion dollar company and diverse in many areas but the impact and negative press will not let up until there is equitable resolution.  Regardless, Taylor wins. That's my humble take on this poorly thought out purchase.
